    pearls: ["Nephrogenic DI means the kidneys CANNOT respond to ADH — ADH levels are normal or elevated, but the collecting duct water channels are dysfunctional; this is the opposite of central DI where ADH production is deficient","The DDAVP challenge test is the key differentiating test: in central DI, desmopressin concentrates the urine; in nephrogenic DI, desmopressin has NO effect because the problem is at the kidney, not the pituitary","Lithium is the most common medication cause of NDI — it enters collecting duct cells through ENaC channels and downregulates aquaporin-2 expression; amiloride specifically blocks this entry pathway","Thiazide diuretics paradoxically REDUCE urine output in DI — this counterintuitive mechanism works by inducing mild volume depletion that increases proximal tubular reabsorption, reducing distal delivery","NEVER restrict fluids in a patient with NDI who has an intact thirst mechanism — the polydipsia is compensatory; fluid restriction will cause dangerous hypernatremia","Correct hypernatremia slowly: no faster than 10-12 mEq/L per 24 hours; too-rapid correction can cause cerebral edema and seizures (the brain has adapted to hyperosmolality by generating idiogenic osmoles)","In congenital X-linked NDI, male infants present with unexplained fevers, failure to thrive, and recurrent dehydration — early diagnosis prevents brain damage from repeated hypernatremic episodes"],
