    pearls: ["Non-contrast CT is the imaging gold standard for suspected nephrolithiasis — ultrasound is first-line only in pregnancy and pediatrics; MRI does not visualize stones directly","NSAIDs (ketorolac) are first-line for renal colic analgesia — they reduce ureteral spasm and are as effective as opioids with fewer side effects; always consider renal function before prescribing","An obstructing stone with concurrent infection (fever + hydronephrosis + positive urine culture) is a urologic emergency requiring emergent decompression (ureteral stent or nephrostomy) — antibiotics alone will not resolve an obstructed infected system","24-hour urine metabolic evaluation is the cornerstone of recurrence prevention — order after acute episode resolves; identifies specific metabolic abnormalities to guide targeted pharmacotherapy","Do NOT advise patients to restrict dietary calcium — adequate calcium (1,000-1,200 mg/day with meals) actually REDUCES stone risk by binding dietary oxalate in the gut; calcium supplements taken without food may increase risk","Stone size and location predict likelihood of spontaneous passage: <5 mm stones pass 90% of the time; 5-10 mm stones pass ~50%; >10 mm rarely pass spontaneously and usually require intervention","Uric acid stones are radiolucent on plain X-ray but visible on CT; they are the only common stone type that can be dissolved medically with urinary alkalinization (potassium citrate to pH 6.5-7.0)"],
